{"id":"2010.02045","submitter":"Claus Scheiderer","authors":"Tim Kobert, Claus Scheiderer","title":"Spectrahedral representation of polar orbitopes","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.OC","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Let $K$ be a compact Lie group and $V$ a finite-dimensional representation of\n$K$. The orbitope of a vector $x\\in V$ is the convex hull $\\mathscr O_x$ of the\norbit $Kx$ in $V$. We show that if $V$ is polar then $\\mathscr O_x$ is a\nspectrahedron, and we produce an explicit linear matrix inequality\nrepresentation. We also consider the coorbitope $\\mathscr O_x^o$, which is the\nconvex set polar to $\\mathscr O_x$. We prove that $\\mathscr O_x^o$ is the\nconvex hull of finitely many $K$-orbits, and we identify the cases in which\n$\\mathscr O_x^o$ is itself an orbitope. In these cases one has $\\mathscr\nO_x^o=c\\cdot\\mathscr O_x$ with $c>0$. Moreover we show that if $x$ has\n\"rational coefficients\" then $\\mathscr O_x^o$ is again a spectrahedron. This\nprovides many new families of doubly spectrahedral orbitopes. All polar\norbitopes that are derived from classical semisimple Lie can be described in\nterms of conditions on singular values and Ky Fan matrix norms.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 5 Oct 2020 14:22:14 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-10-06"}
