{"id":"2010.02760","submitter":"Guoping Wang","authors":"Xu Chen, Guoping Wang","title":"The distance spectrum of the complements of graphs of diameter greater\n  than three","comments":"8 pages, 10 conferences","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Suppose that $G$ is a connected simple graph with the vertex set $V( G ) = \\{\nv_1,v_2,\\cdots ,v_n \\} $. Let $d( v_i,v_j ) $ be the distance between $v_i$ and\n$v_j$. Then the distance matrix of $G$ is $D( G ) =( d_{ij} )_{n\\times n}$,\nwhere $d_{ij}=d( v_i,v_j ) $. Since $D( G )$ is a non-negative real symmetric\nmatrix, its eigenvalues can be arranged $\\lambda_1(G)\\ge \\lambda_2(G)\\ge \\cdots\n\\ge \\lambda_n(G)$, where eigenvalues $\\lambda_1(G)$ and $\\lambda_n(G)$ are\ncalled the distance spectral radius and the least distance eigenvalue of $G$,\nrespectively. The {\\it diameter} of graph $G$ is the farthest distance between\nall pairs of vertices. In this paper, we determine the unique graph whose\ndistance spectral radius attains maximum and minimum among all complements of\ngraphs of diameter greater than three, respectively. Furthermore, we also\ncharacterize the unique graph whose least distance eigenvalue attains maximum\nand minimum among all complements of graphs of diameter greater than three,\nrespectively.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 5 Oct 2020 05:00:24 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 3 Nov 2020 08:49:01 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-11-04"}
